  "description": "Interval-set algebra modelled on the intervaltree library: mergeOverlaps (merge_overlaps strict=False, coalescing touching intervals)/overlaps/chop over half-open Int intervals, with witness (same point set) and canonicality (sorted, nonempty, strict-gap disjoint) specs for mergeOverlaps anchored on the frozen `covered` point-membership predicate. Scope: `mergeOverlaps` models `merge_overlaps(strict=False)` — it coalesces touching (not just overlapping) intervals; interval `data` payloads and merge reducers are dropped (bare `[lo, hi)` intervals only). The benchmark curates the SET-ALGEBRA subset (overlaps / mergeOverlaps / chop), NOT the searchable IntervalTree query API (`at` / `overlap` / `envelop`). Beyond the headline witness+canonicality obligations the suite includes a deep hidden-invariant layer: canonical-form UNIQUENESS (coverage determines the literal output list), per-output endpoint saturation/maximality (`saturated_lo`/`saturated_hi`, left/right gap-boundary uncoveredness, run-solidity), the union homomorphism and concat-closure laws on point sets, the whole-shape `disjointSortedNonempty` invariant, and cross-API `mergeOverlaps`x`chop` list-equality laws (pre-merge absorption, chop idempotence-up-to-canonical, chop coverage-determines). Each clean END statement hides a discovered strengthened induction hypothesis (the strict-gap separation engine, the per-member boundary lemmas, the coverage-uniqueness bridge) whose machinery lives only in the curator soundness proof.",
